node.text:
The glorious Cotswold hotel @thyme.england was founded with an ethos of caring for and celebrating the land, an ethos expressed through its beautiful gardens, botanically inspired decoration, and seasonal cooking based around locally grown (often home-grown) produce. This summer (starting June 15) Thyme is staging its first exhibition in the estate's restored Tithe Barn – a celebration of the country meadow in pressed flowers by Brixton-based @jamjar_flowers. In time for the launch of the exhibition on June 15, the JamJar team have created a charming tutorial on how to press flowers especially for House & Garden.

Film by @frederickjewson
Thanks to @long_elgar

node.title: How to press flowers with JamJar and Thyme

node.text: March is the month when seed sowing starts in earnest, and our own @clarefostergardens has been preparing hers in her garden in Berkshire. In this video from her greenhouse, she talks us through how to sow seeds, discussing the the vegetables she's sowing, like chard and beetroot, and flowers like calendula and phlox.

node.title: How to sow seeds with our garden editor Clare Foster

Expect more from us over the coming weeks. For now we urge you to support @blklivesmatter and @blmuk, and keep the conversation about how we can change going forward.

node.text:
When its current owners took it on, Lamb's House in Leith was a shadow of its seventeenth-century self, an uneasy whole thanks to its many guises over the years. Once one of the wealthiest houses in the area, it became almost a ruin in the 1930s and spent the 1970s as an old people's day centre. In 2010, following a narrow escape from a property developer, it was bought by the conservation architects Kristin Hannesdottir and Nick Groves-Raines of @grovesraines, and has now been restored in spectacular fashion with a mix of contemporary and venerable pieces. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸@davidelovatti

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in East Hampton, New York. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

node.text:
Perched on an East Hampton lane only a few paces from the beach, this 18th-century colonial house is a testament to the power of decorative reinvention. @stevengambrel, the New York-based designer, had been here before. The previous English owners wanted the house to feel like a Cotswold cottage, and he had decorated it accordingly, but its new owners asked him to return and reinterpret it in a way that better reflected its coastal setting and their lifestyle.

To read the full story and see the interiors, pick up a copy of our September issue, out now. You can currently get a trial offer of 3 issues of House & Garden for only £1 with free home delivery and instant access to the digital edition. Follow the link in our profile to get this offer.

Ceramicist @EdmunddeWaal – in whose hands porcelain becomes something almost mesmerising – has allowed us a glimpse inside the calm, minimalist world of his London studio as he prepares for his next show. Follow the link in our profile for the full video.

node.text:
This country house in East Sussex was almost derelict when Richard Smith and Andrew Blackman fell in love with it. Together, they have breathed new life into the 17th-century property and made extensive use of Richard’s own playful fabric designs for his company @madeauxhome. On either side of the chimneypiece, which was moved from a local farmhouse in the early 20th century, are armchairs covered in Madeaux’s alpaca/wool ‘Berber Stripe’. The ottoman has a skirt in Madeaux’s ‘Tallulah’ linen.

To read the full story, pick up a copy of our September issue, out now. You can currently get a trial offer of 3 issues of House & Garden for only £1 with free home delivery and instant access to the digital edition. Follow the link in our profile to get this offer.

📸@paul_massey

node.text:
When Libby Russell of @mazzullorussell discovered Batcombe House, a seventeenth-century rectory with Georgian additions, she fell in love. ‘The valley has a sort of timelessness about it and a strong sense of natural beauty,’ she says. ‘I wanted to make a garden that relates to its landscape, so it’s all about the animals in the fields around and how you connect one side of the valley to the other.’ Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸 @eva_nemeth 

Mazzullo + Russell is a member of @thelistbyhouseandgarden

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in Donhead St Mary. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
Thirty years after creating the timeless gardens at Shute House in Dorset, landscape architect Sir Geoffrey Jellicoe was tempted out of retirement to revitalise them for its new owners, in what would transpire to be his final project. The garden is a place of quiet reflection and tranquillity, laced with theatrical delight. Black swans inhabit the waters on the formal lake, which is surrounded by ferns and wisteria. Follow the link in our profile to see more.
📸 Sabina Rüber

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in London, United Kingdom. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
'These tiny Victorian chimneypieces are such piglets,' says Wendy Nicholls of @sibylcolefax, referring to those in her London mansion flat. 'But we couldn't afford to change them.' In the drawing room, she replaced their floral tiles with slate and commissioned the grisaille wall painting, based on one in a room in Sandemar, the seventeenth-century Swedish manor house. 'The columns give the chimneypieces a bit more presence,' she says. 'And I love the serenity of Swedish interiors.' Follow the link in our profile to see the rest of the apartment.
📸 @alexanderjamesphoto

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine on August 03, 2021. May be an image of flower, nature and tree.

node.text:
The first things you notice as you arrive at this rural Italian garden are the huge sky and the open landscape. Set in an unspoilt, underpopulated part of the central Lazio region north of Rome, near volcanic Lake Bolsena, this garden has been created by @stuart_barfoot_garden_design to be in tune with its surroundings. ‘I wanted it to feel as though it was part of nature,’ he says.  The landscape and skies are so strong here that you can’t go against them. The wildlife is amazing, too, so we wanted to bring out what was unique about the location.’ Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸 @montgomeryphoto

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in Surrey. May be an image of outdoors, tree and the Cotswolds.

node.text:
Scandinavia is known for its pale wood-panelled interiors and icy white light; Surrey, for its mellow Lutyens manors and misty rolling hills, so you might have thought it a rather challenging ambition for a London-based Norwegian family to graft a strong flavour of its roots onto a turn-of-the-century Arts and Crafts house. In the end, however, with help from @todhunterearleinteriors, the cosmopolitan blend proved a great success. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸@aliciataylorphotography

Todhunter Earle are members of @thelistbyhouseandgarden

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in London, United Kingdom. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
In her own house in north London, the interior designer @ShaliniMisraLtd has cleverly manipulated the Victorian architecture and collaborated with specialist artisans to bring a feeling of intimacy to its spacious rooms. The house is an elegant, double-fronted Victorian villa: a place where, even without the blue plaque outside, you would get the sense that the walls within have interesting stories to tell. Inside, however, it is clear that Shalini has not shied away from adding her own distinctive narrative to the space, bending it to her will through bold architectural intervention. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸@michaelsinclair

Shalini Misra is a member of @thelistbyhouseandgarden

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in Wiltshire. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
When Harry and Rebecca Whittaker bought a handsome limestone building where weavers once lived and worked, it had very little to recommend it beyond its eighteenth-century windows and views of Bradford on Avon. You would have needed a forensic architectural eye to spot the potential beauty hidden by the render, concrete slabs and featureless rooms. Fortunately, as an experienced conservation architect – ‘but without the tweed suit and mustard trousers,’ he jokes – Harry was well equipped to tackle what, for most people, would be a nightmare project. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸  @paul_massey

Our September issue goes on sale on Thursday, with a host of stories to lift the spirits and provide some escape. Inside you'll find a minimalist holiday house in Puglia (on the cover) owned by the London-based Italian architect Lorenzo Grifantini of @dosarchitects, and a rather different retreat in the Hamptons, decorated by @stevengambrel with period chic. Elsewhere in the US, a dream log cabin has been brought to life on a Texas ranch, with interiors by @m_interiors_tx, while closer to home, a 17th-century house in East Sussex has been rescued from a semi-derelict state by its new owners. 

Don't miss this month's gardens, a varied London garden by @tommasseyuk that includes a woodland wilderness, a pretty potager and elegant formal areas, and a South African garden in harmony with its arid surroundings in the Karoo.
